    	<h2><a name="2003-07-09" href="#2003-07-09"><font color="#660000">2003-07-09</font></a></h2>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="105776809372135218">&nbsp;</a><br>
	.&nbsp; The "Blog This" interactions and logon requirement are becoming really tiresome.&nbsp; I have had my moments of truth, I just need to figure out when I will spend time on an alternative.<br /><br />Meanwhile, here's an interesting CNET article on the secure identity wars.  There is a lot of room here for white papers and how-to-do-it items on managing secure identities, trust relationships, and so on.  The key thing is transparency, I would say. At the moment, learning about certificates and the little padlock symbol is completely inscrutable for people.  So, WS-Federation strikes me as the right idea.  And I continue to see IBM as the honest broker here in the interoperability and other wars that are poorly-disguised efforts at containing the Borg.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#105776809372135218">Wednesday, July 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	
    	<h2><a name="2003-07-08" href="#2003-07-08"><font color="#660000">2003-07-08</font></a></h2>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="105768300075022002">&nbsp;</a><br>
	.&nbsp; This new Blog This interface is really annoying.<br /><br />All right, the ebXML folk have advanced their registry specifications to version 2.5 and there are now federated registries and other interesting possibilities.&nbsp; Hmm, I should be able to dig into all of this in my next course on Web Applications.&nbsp; Good, it is about time I took this to another level.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#105768300075022002">Tuesday, July 08, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="105768267692749801">&nbsp;</a><br>
	.nbsp; Here's a nice organization and approach.  The focus on interoperability combined with enterprise architecture is very appealing to me.&nbsp; A reminder that I need to update my resource pages to provide links as well as bibliographies, and I need a way to scrape my blog for the accumulated links.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#105768267692749801">Tuesday, July 08, 2003</a></span></div>
